INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(113, 1, '2012-08-21 13:46:52', '2012-08-21 13:46:52', 'Join the Young Foundation and Action for Happiness at Dartington for the Interrogate! Happiness Festival, your chance to spend a weekend looking at what makes us happy.\r\nThe festival will explore such questions as: How can we learn to be happy at work, in our families and at school? Is mindfulness the new religion when it comes to happiness? Is it possible for government policy to contribute to happiness and wellebeing, and if so, how?\r\nThe event will be two days of transformative, participative and action orientated discussion, music, comedy, film and spoken word both by and for people who want to make the world a happier place. Try out laughter yoga or Tai Chi, boost your positive thinking and learn to be kinder. The speaker line-up so far includes former Young Foundation CEO Geoff Mulgan, happiness economist Richard Layard, and academic and social thinker Maurice Glasman.\r\nThe festival will be held at Dartington Hall, Michael Young''s much beloved school where he was a student, trustee, and deputy chairman.  When awarded a peerage, he chose for himself the title "Baron Young of Dartington."\r\nInterrogate! Happiness is a new way to explore an important issue and have fun while you do it, whether your interest is professional, personal or both.\r\nYou can spend an hour, a day or the whole weekend. So forget your troubles, come on, get happy!', 'Interrogate! Happiness Festival', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '111-revision-2', '', '', '2012-08-21 13:46:52', '2012-08-21 13:46:52', '', 111, 'http://localhost:8888/young_foundation/111-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(114, 1, '2012-08-21 13:46:06', '2012-08-21 13:46:06', 'As part of the London Design Festival, speakers from the team behind social venture Care4Care will talk about their use of design approaches to create this venture through a process of participatory innovation. The brainchild of Professor Heinz Wolff, Care4Care offers a new approach to one of the most pressing challenges facing many societies today: how to care for ageing populations now, and how to ensure that people will be cared for in the future.  Care4Care provides support for older people through mutual exchange supported by a time-banking system. Members earn ‘care credits'' by caring for an older person in their local community. The hours of support members provide are recorded in their individual care credit account for the member''s own future use or to support a relative or friend now.\r\nTo design this venture, the team have been using a range of approaches from fields such as venturing, service design, the social sciences and management, with support from Age UK. Methods used include undertaking user research, iterative prototyping, participatory design, service blueprinting, organisational analysis and change management. Using design strategically has been central to crafting the proposition, engaging volunteers, and learning from prototyping. For all those interested in the inner workings of social design, or if you just want to shake the hands of Team Care4Care, we''ll be pleased to see you there.', 'Care 4 Care at the London Design Festival', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '109-revision-2', '', '', '2012-08-21 13:46:06', '2012-08-21 13:46:06', '', 109, 'http://localhost:8888/young_foundation/109-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(115, 1, '2012-08-21 13:47:50', '2012-08-21 13:47:50', 'Join Young Foundation venture <a href="http://www.youngfoundation.org/our-ventures?current_venture=1943">Action for Happiness</a> for an entertaining and thought-provoking evening as comedian and broadcaster <a href="https://twitter.com/Rubywax">Ruby Wax</a> gives us an exclusive preview of her new show about how learning to be "mindful" can help us cope better with the pressures of modern life.\r\n\r\nIn her own unique style, Ruby will share what she''s learnt about why people "burn out", how this relates to the inner workings of the human brain, and how learning a skill like mindfulness can help us cope better with life''s ups and downs.\r\n\r\nRuby Wax is one of Britain''s best-loved comedians, writers, and mental health campaigners and has spent three decades working on stage, television and radio.\r\n\r\nRuby has done a huge amount to raise awareness of mental illness and help end the stigma associated with depression. She has spoken openly about her own battles with depression and is an ambassador for the Time to Change campaign.\r\n\r\nThis event will take place at <a href="http://www.conwayhall.org.uk/visiting-us">Conway Hall</a> in central London on Wednesday 15 August 2012. Doors will open at 18:45 and the event will start at 19:00.', 'An evening with Ruby Wax', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'an-evening-with-ruby-wax', '', '', '2012-08-21 13:48:40', '2012-08-21 13:48:40', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/young_foundation/?p=115', 0, 'post', '', 0);
